Under --no-input, any branch that would prompt becomes a deterministic error rather
than a silent default-accept (the GLOBAL --no-input rule). A name has no inferable
default, so omitting it is a usage error (exit 2), naming the positional argument.

```
$ rackabel new --no-input
? 2
error: a project name is required [RK0101]
  help: pass it as the first argument, e.g. `rackabel new <name>` (running with --no-input, so I won't prompt for it)
(run `rackabel explain RK0101` for details)

```
